3":"1433","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1390":"1390","1416":"1416","1449":"1449","Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England":"Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Odell, Bedfordshire, England":"Odell, Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wheeler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a wheelwright, a maker of wheels (primarily for carts and other vehicles, but also other kinds of wheels, for use in spinning or other manufacturing processes), from Middle English <i>wheler</i>, <i>whegheler</i>, a derivative of Old English <i>hweogol</i>, <i>hweowol</i>, <i>hwēol</i> ‘wheel’.","History: A founder of Salisbury, NH, in 1634 was John Wheeler."],"variants":[{"name":"Rower","meanings":["English: occupational name from Anglo-Norman French <i>roer</i> ‘wheelwright’ (Old French <i>roier</i>, <i>rouwier</i>, <i>rouer</i>, an agent derivative of <i>roue</i> ‘wheel’). Compare   Wheeler  .","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>rouer(e)</i> ‘rower, oarsman’. Compare   Rother  .","German (<b>Röwer</b>): unexplained."]},{"name":"Wheelwright","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): occupational name from Middle English <i>whelewright(e)</i>, <i>whelrihte</i> ‘wheelwright, maker of wheels and wheeled vehicles’ (Old English <i>hwēol</i> + <i>wyrhta</i>). See also   Wheeler  .","History: John Wheelwright (<i>c.</i> 1592–1679), clergyman, came to Boston, MA, from Lincolnshire, England in 1636. He was banished from Massachusettes for his support of his sister-in-law, Anne Hutchinson, in the antinomian controversy; he set up a community at Exeter, NH."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":39,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Wheeler was born in 1416, in Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England, his father, Richard Wheeler, was 17 and his mother, Mary Elizabeth Booth, was 26. He married Joan Robyn in 1440, in Odell, Bedfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1470, in his hometown, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1416–1470":"1416–1470","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1420–1455":"1420–1455","1433–1470":"1433–1470","1449–Male":"1449–Surnud","1452–Male":"1452–Surnud","1399–1435":"1399–1435","1390–1440":"1390–1440","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1390":"1390","1416":"1416","1449":"1449","Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England":"Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Odell, Bedfordshire, England":"Odell, Bedfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1416–1470":"1416–1470","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","1420–1455":"1420–1455","1433–1470":"1433–1470","1449–Male":"1449–Kuollut","1452–Male":"1452–Kuollut","1399–1435":"1399–1435","1390–144